	<task type="small talk">
		<turn type="chatbot" who="ChatGPT">Let's jump into a real example! What are you working on or curious about that you'd like to explore more deeply?</turn>
		<turn type="student"><DMCC corr="Can">can</DMCC> you give me a topic to start a conversation?</turn>
		<turn type="chatbot" who="ChatGPT">Sure! Here’s a great conversation starter:
		"If you could instantly master any skill or learn something new overnight, what would it be and why?"
		It's broad enough to invite various interesting perspectives but also personal, sparking deeper discussions.
		What skill would you choose?</turn>
		<turn type="student"><DMCC corr="I">i</DMCC>'d love to learn as <GDI corr="many">much</GDI> languages as possible</turn>
		<turn type="chatbot" who="ChatGPT">That’s an amazing goal! Learning multiple languages can open up so many opportunities for travel, work, and connecting with different cultures.
		What draws you most to learning languages? Is it the cultural aspect, communication, or something else? And do you have any specific languages you’d like to start with?</turn>
		<turn type="student"><DMCC corr="The">the</DMCC> <GWC corr="cultural">culture</GWC> aspect is what I like most about learning a new language, <FS corr="even">eve</FS> the backstories behind it, <Z corr="?">the social face of the same language</Z></turn>
		<turn type="chatbot" who="ChatGPT">That’s a fascinating motivation! Language and culture are so intertwined, and each language holds its own unique worldview, expressions, and traditions. For instance, in Japanese, the idea of “wabi-sabi” (finding beauty in imperfection) is deeply cultural and shapes how people speak about aesthetics and life. 
		Exploring backstories can also reveal interesting language roots. For example, Spanish and Arabic have influenced each other deeply, especially in southern Spain due to historical Moorish presence, which shaped the culture and language in that region.
		Is there a specific language or culture whose backstory you find especially intriguing?</turn>
		<turn type="student"><DMCC corr="Every">every</DMCC> African language has a great history behind that <WO corr="is usually">usually is</WO> ignored by the big <GNN corr="university">universities</GNN> programs so <GPP corr="it">\0</GPP> <GVAUX corr="is">\0</GVAUX> hard to learn in the first place</turn>
		<turn type="chatbot" who="ChatGPT">You're absolutely right! African languages often carry deep histories and rich cultural significance that are sadly underrepresented in mainstream education, especially in larger university programs. Each African language reflects the social, spiritual, and historical experiences of its people. For instance, languages like Swahili have roots in Bantu, Arabic, and Persian, reflecting centuries of trade and cultural exchange along the East African coast.
		Moreover, many African languages are oral traditions, meaning their histories are often passed down through storytelling, music, and rituals, rather than written texts. This makes them incredibly unique but also harder to study through typical academic programs.
		What African language are you most interested in learning, and what aspect of its history or culture fascinates you the most?</turn>
		<turn type="student"><DMCC corr="I">i</DMCC>'m following a program at university that gives me the opportunity to study Hausa or Swahili, I'm <XVPR corr="thinking about">thinking </XVPR> one of those</turn>
		<turn type="chatbot" who="ChatGPT">Both Hausa and Swahili are excellent choices, each with a fascinating history and cultural significance! Here's a bit about both to help you decide:
		Hausa
		Region: Predominantly spoken in Northern Nigeria and Niger, but also in parts of Ghana, Cameroon, and Sudan.
		Cultural Importance: Hausa is part of the Chadic language family and is one of the most widely spoken languages in West Africa. It’s deeply tied to Islamic culture and is a primary language of trade, media, and literature in the region.
		History: Hausa has been influenced by Arabic due to historical Islamic ties and is one of the few African languages with a longstanding tradition of written literature, particularly in Ajami (a form of Arabic script).
		Why study it: If you’re interested in West African trade, Islamic scholarship, or the cultural dynamics of the Sahel, Hausa offers a rich linguistic and cultural landscape.
		Swahili
		Region: Swahili is spoken in East African countries like Kenya, Tanzania, Uganda, and parts of the Democratic Republic of Congo. It serves as a lingua franca in the region.
		Cultural Importance: It’s a Bantu language, but heavily influenced by Arabic, due to centuries of Indian Ocean trade, and also by Portuguese and English colonization.
		History: Swahili’s development is tied to trade along the East African coast, with cultural exchange between Africans, Arabs, Persians, and later Europeans. Swahili is also the working language of the African Union and one of the most popular African languages in academia.
		Why study it: If you’re drawn to East African coastal culture, international diplomacy, or the blend of African and Arab traditions, Swahili would give you access to a wide, culturally diverse region.
		Swahili might appeal to you if you like exploring languages that have influenced global communication and trade, while Hausa offers insight into a historically rich region connected through trade and Islamic scholarship.
		Which of these cultural aspects aligns more with your personal or professional interests?</turn>
		<turn type="student"><DMCC corr="Alright">alright</DMCC> thanks</turn>
		<turn type="chatbot" who="ChatGPT">You're welcome! Glad I could help. Whichever language you choose, you're in for a rewarding journey into rich cultural and historical landscapes. If you ever need more insights or help with your studies, feel free to ask! Good luck with your program!</turn>
	</task>
	<task type="role play">
